article.description: Paul Pierce had 22 points and 10 rebounds, scoring 11 during a 14-0 fourth-quarter run as the Boston Celtics beat Cleveland 96-70 to sweep the season series against the Cavaliers.
article.headline: Celtics outscore Cavs 54-29 after halftime
article.linkText: C's shut down Cavs in second half to sweep series
article.story:
BOSTON (AP) -- Cleveland helped Boston's playoff chances for the second straight night -- this time by losing.
Pierce

Paul Pierce had 22 points and 10 rebounds, scoring 11 during a 14-0 fourth-quarter run as the Celtics beat the Cavaliers 96-70 Wednesday night to sweep the season series against Cleveland. The loss to the Atlantic Division's No. 2 team came a night after the Cavs beat first-place New Jersey on a disputed, last-second shot. "A game like that takes a lot out of you," Cleveland center Chris Mihm said, "not only physically but mentally." With the win, Boston remained four games behind the Nets in the Atlantic Division. The Celtics had lost consecutive games after winning seven straight. "It was important for us to get the 'W,"' Pierce said after showing off the bobble-head doll in his likeness given to the first 5,000 fans. "It was important for us to get some momentum back." Antoine Walker had 17 points, seven rebounds and nine assists for the Celtics, who last swept Cleveland in 1984-85. Kenny Anderson added 13 points, nine rebounds and six assists before sitting out the final minutes with the rest of the starters following a 21-2 run that turned a nine-point game into a blowout. Wesley Person had 17 points and Andre Miller had nine points, seven assists and seven rebounds for Cleveland, which had won two in a row but was playing its fourth game in five nights. Mihm had 12 points and nine rebounds. On Tuesday, the Cavaliers beat New Jersey when Lamond Murray made a jumper in the final half-second after the clock was slow to start. On Wednesday, the Celtics didn't give Cleveland any last chances. Boston led 69-60 with 8:53 left before scoring the next 14 points -- 11 of the first 12 by Pierce. After Mihm made a basket, the Celtics ran off seven points in a row -- three from Anderson and four from Walker -- to take a 26-point lead. Pierce also made a 53-footer at the end of the first half, pulling down a rebound with 2.8 seconds left, dribbling and letting fly from the far 3-point circle that swished in after the buzzer to make it 42-41. "It was a lucky, lucky shot," Boston coach Jim O'Brien said. "He practices it a lot, much to my dismay. ... That was a nice gift." Boston fell behind early in the third before Walker had five points, two assists and a steal during an 11-0 run that made it 55-47 with 7:23 left. The Celtics never trailed again, though Cleveland did cut it to three points before Boston scored eight consecutive points, including five in a row by Pierce in the final minute to make it 65-53 after three quarters. Game notes
Former Celtics great Bill Russell attended the game, receiving a standing ovation in the fourth quarter. ... Cleveland C Zydrunas Ilgauskas was a late scratch from the starting lineup one night after scoring 26 points with 14 rebounds. He entered the game in the second quarter. ... Cavs F Tyrone Hill was sidelined with a severe sinus infection and was not with the team. ... The Celtics have won all but one of the games Vitaly Potapenko has started this year. ... Pierce entered the game leading the NBA in fourth-quarter points with 457.
